[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":442},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fjs-from-zero-09-logical-operators\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fjs-from-zero-09-logical-operators\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fjs-from-zero-09-logical-operators\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fjs-from-zero-09-logical-operators\u002F":418,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fjs-from-zero-09-logical-operators\u002F":427},"\u002Fjavascript\u002F20190924\u002F2350948424\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":401,"date":402,"description":403,"extension":404,"lang":405,"meta":406,"navigation":362,"path":407,"readingMinutes":408,"seo":409,"standalone":410,"stem":411,"tags":412,"tldr":415,"updated":402,"url":416,"__hash__":417},"content\u002Fen\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-from-zero-09-logical-operators.md","RE: Learning JS From Zero — Day 9: Logical Operators (and Why They Don't Always Return true\u002Ffalse)","1002256918",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":391},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,41,55,103,117,120,127,131,140,214,218,231,259,263,275,306,310,313,317,320,337,380,384,387],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Day 9 of getting reincarnated into JS land. Back on Day 6 we went through operators, but there was one group we never touched — the logical operators. So this time we're filling that gap.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"logical-operators","Logical Operators",[17,25,26,27,31,32,35,36,40],{},"In an earlier chapter we figured out that comparison operators take two values (or variables), compare them, and hand back ",[28,29,30],"code",{},"true"," or ",[28,33,34],{},"false",". So what about logical operators? They work a little differently. A logical operator waits for the comparison operators to finish comparing first, and ",[37,38,39],"em",{},"then"," does its logical judgement on top of that.",[17,42,43,44,47,48,50,51,54],{},"Here's an example. Say I've got two pairs of numbers, and I want to compare each pair and then make one more logical decision — I want to know whether ",[37,45,46],{},"both"," comparisons came out ",[28,49,30],{},". For that I'd reach for the ",[28,52,53],{},"&&"," (AND) operator:",[56,57,62],"pre",{"className":58,"code":59,"language":60,"meta":61,"style":61},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","(5 > 2 && 10 \u003C 25); \u002F\u002F true\n","js","",[28,63,64],{"__ignoreMap":61},[65,66,69,73,77,81,84,87,90,93,96,99],"span",{"class":67,"line":68},"line",1,[65,70,72],{"class":71},"sMAXC","(",[65,74,76],{"class":75},"sCcAr","5",[65,78,80],{"class":79},"sWyjQ"," >",[65,82,83],{"class":75}," 2",[65,85,86],{"class":79}," &&",[65,88,89],{"class":75}," 10",[65,91,92],{"class":79}," \u003C",[65,94,95],{"class":75}," 25",[65,97,98],{"class":71},"); ",[65,100,102],{"class":101},"sQrFR","\u002F\u002F true\n",[17,104,105,107,108,110,111,113,114,116],{},[28,106,53],{}," means: only return ",[28,109,30],{}," if ",[37,112,46],{}," sides come out ",[28,115,30],{},".",[17,118,119],{},"There are three main logical operators:",[17,121,122],{},[123,124],"img",{"alt":125,"src":126},"Logical operators","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FQiwIxUV.png",[12,128,130],{"id":129},"and-operator","AND Operator",[17,132,133,134,136,137,139],{},"I already showed AND a second ago. In short: if even one side comes out ",[28,135,34],{},", the whole thing returns ",[28,138,34],{},". For example:",[56,141,143],{"className":58,"code":142,"language":60,"meta":61,"style":61},"(5 > 2 && 10 \u003C 25); \u002F\u002F true\n(5 > 2 && 10 \u003C 25); \u002F\u002F true\n(5 > 2 && 10 > 25); \u002F\u002F false\n",[28,144,145,167,190],{"__ignoreMap":61},[65,146,147,149,151,153,155,157,159,161,163,165],{"class":67,"line":68},[65,148,72],{"class":71},[65,150,76],{"class":75},[65,152,80],{"class":79},[65,154,83],{"class":75},[65,156,86],{"class":79},[65,158,89],{"class":75},[65,160,92],{"class":79},[65,162,95],{"class":75},[65,164,98],{"class":71},[65,166,102],{"class":101},[65,168,170,172,174,176,178,180,182,184,186,188],{"class":67,"line":169},2,[65,171,72],{"class":71},[65,173,76],{"class":75},[65,175,80],{"class":79},[65,177,83],{"class":75},[65,179,86],{"class":79},[65,181,89],{"class":75},[65,183,92],{"class":79},[65,185,95],{"class":75},[65,187,98],{"class":71},[65,189,102],{"class":101},[65,191,193,195,197,199,201,203,205,207,209,211],{"class":67,"line":192},3,[65,194,72],{"class":71},[65,196,76],{"class":75},[65,198,80],{"class":79},[65,200,83],{"class":75},[65,202,86],{"class":79},[65,204,89],{"class":75},[65,206,80],{"class":79},[65,208,95],{"class":75},[65,210,98],{"class":71},[65,212,213],{"class":101},"\u002F\u002F false\n",[12,215,217],{"id":216},"or-operator","OR Operator",[17,219,220,221,224,225,227,228,230],{},"OR is easy to wrap your head around — as long as ",[37,222,223],{},"one"," side is ",[28,226,30],{},", it returns ",[28,229,30],{},":",[56,232,234],{"className":58,"code":233,"language":60,"meta":61,"style":61},"(5 > 2 || 10 > 25); \u002F\u002F true\n",[28,235,236],{"__ignoreMap":61},[65,237,238,240,242,244,246,249,251,253,255,257],{"class":67,"line":68},[65,239,72],{"class":71},[65,241,76],{"class":75},[65,243,80],{"class":79},[65,245,83],{"class":75},[65,247,248],{"class":79}," ||",[65,250,89],{"class":75},[65,252,80],{"class":79},[65,254,95],{"class":75},[65,256,98],{"class":71},[65,258,102],{"class":101},[12,260,262],{"id":261},"not-operator","NOT Operator",[17,264,265,266,269,270,272,273,230],{},"This one just flips the result. You'll see it most often in places like ",[28,267,268],{},"if (!a) {...}",". So something that was originally ",[28,271,34],{}," gets flipped to ",[28,274,30],{},[56,276,278],{"className":58,"code":277,"language":60,"meta":61,"style":61},"!(5 > 2 && 10 > 25); \u002F\u002F was false, flipped to true\n",[28,279,280],{"__ignoreMap":61},[65,281,282,285,287,289,291,293,295,297,299,301,303],{"class":67,"line":68},[65,283,284],{"class":79},"!",[65,286,72],{"class":71},[65,288,76],{"class":75},[65,290,80],{"class":79},[65,292,83],{"class":75},[65,294,86],{"class":79},[65,296,89],{"class":75},[65,298,80],{"class":79},[65,300,95],{"class":75},[65,302,98],{"class":71},[65,304,305],{"class":101},"\u002F\u002F was false, flipped to true\n",[12,307,309],{"id":308},"key-point","Key Point",[17,311,312],{},"One last thing to keep in mind: a logical operator waits for the comparison operators to finish before doing its logical judgement. But here's the catch — once you've got two or more logical operators chained together, things get a bit different, and you run into dependency issues (we'll cover that in a later chapter).",[12,314,316],{"id":315},"kuros-addition","Kuro's Addition",[17,318,319],{},"Big thanks to Kuro for the extra note here~~~",[321,322,323],"blockquote",{},[17,324,325,326,328,329,332,333,31,335,116],{},"Operators like ",[28,327,53],{}," and ",[28,330,331],{},"||"," — everyone calls them logical operators, but the thing they hand back isn't necessarily ",[28,334,30],{},[28,336,34],{},[56,338,340],{"className":58,"code":339,"language":60,"meta":61,"style":61},"0 && 1;    \u002F\u002F it will return 0\n\n0 || 'a';  \u002F\u002F it will return 'a'\n",[28,341,342,358,364],{"__ignoreMap":61},[65,343,344,347,349,352,355],{"class":67,"line":68},[65,345,346],{"class":75},"0",[65,348,86],{"class":79},[65,350,351],{"class":75}," 1",[65,353,354],{"class":71},";    ",[65,356,357],{"class":101},"\u002F\u002F it will return 0\n",[65,359,360],{"class":67,"line":169},[65,361,363],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":362},true,"\n",[65,365,366,368,370,374,377],{"class":67,"line":192},[65,367,346],{"class":75},[65,369,248],{"class":79},[65,371,373],{"class":372},"sTRMh"," 'a'",[65,375,376],{"class":71},";  ",[65,378,379],{"class":101},"\u002F\u002F it will return 'a'\n",[12,381,383],{"id":382},"wrapping-up","Wrapping Up",[17,385,386],{},"Next up in RE: Learning JS From Zero — Day 10, we'll get into conditional statements.",[388,389,390],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sQrFR, html code.shiki .sQrFR{--shiki-default:#BDC4CC}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}",{"title":61,"searchDepth":169,"depth":169,"links":392},[393,394,395,396,397,398,399,400],{"id":14,"depth":169,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":169,"text":23},{"id":129,"depth":169,"text":130},{"id":216,"depth":169,"text":217},{"id":261,"depth":169,"text":262},{"id":308,"depth":169,"text":309},{"id":315,"depth":169,"text":316},{"id":382,"depth":169,"text":383},"JavaScript","2019-09-24 00:00:15","Day 9 of getting reincarnated into JS land. Back on Day 6 we covered operators, but we skipped the logical operators — &&, ||, and !. So this time we'll fill that gap, walk through what each one does, and end with a neat catch from Kuro: these operators don't always hand you a clean true or false.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002Fjs-from-zero-09-logical-operators","2",{"title":6,"description":403},false,"en\u002FJavaScript\u002Fjs-from-zero-09-logical-operators",[401,413,414],"RE：從零開始的學習 JS 生活","第 11 屆 iT邦幫忙鐵人賽",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fjs-from-zero-09-logical-operators\u002F","y9sXSbezeIqReqUS3IxG_nYUTyk5wLnG3zSeq2L8qOk",{"newer":419,"older":423},{"url":420,"title":421,"date":422},"\u002Fen\u002Fphp\u002F2019\u002F09\u002F24\u002Fthink-php-day-23-form-validation-01\u002F","ThinkPHP Day 23: Form Validation, Part 1","2019-09-24 00:00:26",{"url":424,"title":425,"date":426},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2019\u002F09\u002F23\u002Fjs-from-zero-ep08-anonymous-functions\u002F","JS From Zero EP.8 — Anonymous Functions and IIFEs","2019-09-23 00:02:02",[428,433,438],{"url":429,"title":430,"date":431,"readingMinutes":432},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2026\u002F03\u002F10\u002Fweb-crypto-api-encryption-guide\u002F","No crypto Package, No Node.js — The Web Crypto API Does It All in the Browser","2026-03-10 09:45:08","9",{"url":434,"title":435,"date":436,"readingMinutes":437},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F08\u002Fjquery-why-it-declined\u002F","jQuery Was Once King — So Why Did It Fall Off?","2025-12-08 21:35:24","7",{"url":439,"title":440,"date":441,"readingMinutes":76},"\u002Fen\u002Fjavascript\u002F2025\u002F12\u002F05\u002Fjavascript-generator-functions\u002F","What Are JavaScript Generator Functions (function*)? The Function You Can Pause and Resume","2025-12-05 13:40:31",1784013060016]